== Installation ==
Portage knows the global USE flag <code>vaapi</code> for enabling support for VAAPI in other packages. Enabling this USE flag will pull in {{Package|x11-libs/libva}} automatically:
{{FileBox|filename=/etc/portage/make.conf|lang=bash|1=
USE="... vaapi ..."
}}
The USE flags of libva are:
{{USEflag|package=x11-libs/libva
|opengl+yes
|vdpau
|dummy+++VIDEO_CARDS USE flag: dummy driver
|intel+++VIDEO_CARDS USE flag:see [[Intel]]
|fglrx+++VIDEO_CARDS USE flag:see [[fglrx]]
|nvidia+++VIDEO_CARDS USE flag:see [[nVidia/nvidia-drivers|nvidia-drivers]]
}}

After setting this you want to update your system so the changes take effect:
{{Emerge|params+=--changed-use --deep|@world}}

== Configuration ==
You may need to tweak the config files of the programs, you can make use of VAAPI.

== Usage ==
<tt>vainfo</tt> shows if VAAPI is supported.

== Software support ==
=== VLC ===
VCL supports VAAPI natively. Activate the appropriate codecs through the Preferences menu (Video Acceleration (VA) API).

=== mpv ===
mpv also supports the VAAPI acceleration through the command line option <code>--hwdec=vaapi</code>.

=== MPlayer ===
Currently, the main MPlayer branch doesn't support VAAPI. There is a development branch (<code>hwaccel-vaapi</code>) available on [https://github.com/gbeauchesne/mplayer-vaapi/ GitHub] that supports VAAPI.

Build the VAAPI enabled MPlayer.
{{Cmd
|git clone -b hwaccel-vaapi https://github.com/gbeauchesne/mplayer-vaapi.git vaapi-mplayer
|cd vaapi-mplayer
|./configure --disable-vdpau --enable-vaapi
|make}}

Install the VAAPI enabled MPlayer (not recommended).
{{RootCmd|make install}}
{{Warning|Be extremely careful when installing anything on your system aside of Portage, since it can conflict with the installed files.}}

Instead, configure {{Package|media-video/smplayer}} to use the VAAPI enabled MPlayer executable (Preferences->General->MPlayer executable), then video driver (User defined/vaapi).

